    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-14T02:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-13T01:00:00-05:00" n="1330"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1330">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">103.9169/4034: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stewart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, [<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1944-06-14T01:10:00-06:00"
                            notBefore="1944-06-13T00:00:00-06:00">undated</date>].<lb/>[Received
                        June 14, 1944—3:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>362. Regarding decentralization rollback to a minimum positive list, reference is
                    made to the Department’s circular airgram dated May 25, 11:15 a.m.<note n="39"
                        xml:id="d1330fn39">Not printed.</note> and Department’s A–127 [<hi
                        rend="italic">197</hi>], June 6, 5 [<hi rend="italic">5:05</hi>] p.m. The
                    Nicaraguan Country Agency has accepted the decentralization rollback and will
                    discontinue June 30, 1944, requiring import permits for commodities that are not
                    covered by import recommendations which will then be needed for the positive
                    list only. Exchange control by the Nicaraguan Government will, however, continue
                    for the time being at least since they state they find it necessary. In lieu of
                    import permits, the importer will after July 1 submit his orders with the same
                    number of copies as in the case of import permits to a one-man Nicaraguan
                    Exchange Control Commission for exchange authorization, the disposition of
                    copies remaining the same. Major Thomas Downing<note n="40" xml:id="d1330fn40"
                        >Major Downing was President of the Nicaraguan Junta de Control de Precios
                        and Assistant Collector of Customs.</note> and in his temporary absence,
                    Colonel Irving Lindberg,<note n="41" xml:id="d1330fn41">Colonel Lindberg was
                        Collector General of Customs and High Commissioner in Nicaragua. For
                        correspondence on the duties of Mr. Downing and Mr. Lindberg, see <ref
                            target="#pg_1396">pp. 1396</ref> ff.</note> both Americans, will act as
                    the Exchange Control Commission.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stewart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
